  {"id": "forall", "symbol": "∀", "latex": "\\forall", "category": "logic", "read_as": "for all", "plain_english": "Universal quantifier. 'For every x in S, the property P(x) holds.' Used to make claims about every element of a set.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\forall x \\in \\mathbb{R},\\ x^2 \\geq 0"]},
  {"id": "exists", "symbol": "∃", "latex": "\\exists", "category": "logic", "read_as": "there exists", "plain_english": "Existential quantifier. 'There is at least one x in S such that P(x) holds.'", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\exists x \\in \\mathbb{R},\\ x^2 = 2"]},
  {"id": "exists-unique", "symbol": "∃!", "latex": "\\exists!", "category": "logic", "read_as": "there exists a unique", "plain_english": "Existence and uniqueness: there is exactly one element with the stated property.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\exists!\\, x \\in \\mathbb{R},\\ x^3 = 8"]},
  {"id": "neg", "symbol": "¬", "latex": "\\neg", "category": "logic", "read_as": "not", "plain_english": "Logical negation. ¬P is true iff P is false.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\neg(P \\wedge Q) \\equiv \\neg P \\vee \\neg Q"]},
  {"id": "and", "symbol": "∧", "latex": "\\wedge", "category": "logic", "read_as": "and", "plain_english": "Logical conjunction. P ∧ Q is true iff both P and Q are true.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["P \\wedge Q"]},
  {"id": "or", "symbol": "∨", "latex": "\\vee", "category": "logic", "read_as": "or", "plain_english": "Logical disjunction (inclusive). P ∨ Q is true iff at least one of P, Q is true.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["P \\vee Q"]},
  {"id": "implies", "symbol": "⇒", "latex": "\\Rightarrow", "category": "logic", "read_as": "implies", "plain_english": "Material implication. P ⇒ Q means whenever P holds, Q holds. Vacuously true when P is false.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["x > 0 \\Rightarrow x^2 > 0"]},
  {"id": "iff", "symbol": "⇔", "latex": "\\Leftrightarrow", "category": "logic", "read_as": "if and only if", "plain_english": "Logical equivalence. P ⇔ Q means P and Q have the same truth value.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["x^2 = 1 \\Leftrightarrow x = \\pm 1"]},
  {"id": "therefore", "symbol": "∴", "latex": "\\therefore", "category": "logic", "read_as": "therefore", "plain_english": "Marks a conclusion that follows from previously stated premises.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["P,\\ P \\Rightarrow Q\\ \\therefore Q"]},
  {"id": "because", "symbol": "∵", "latex": "\\because", "category": "logic", "read_as": "because", "plain_english": "Marks a reason or premise supporting a conclusion.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["x = 0\\ \\because\\ x^2 = 0"]},
  {"id": "vdash", "symbol": "⊢", "latex": "\\vdash", "category": "logic", "read_as": "proves", "plain_english": "Syntactic entailment. Γ ⊢ φ means φ is derivable from premises Γ in a formal proof system.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\Gamma \\vdash \\varphi"]},
  {"id": "vDash", "symbol": "⊨", "latex": "\\vDash", "category": "logic", "read_as": "models / entails", "plain_english": "Semantic entailment. Γ ⊨ φ means every model of Γ is a model of φ.", "first_seen_in": "01-logic-and-proof", "examples": ["\\Gamma \\vDash \\varphi"]},
